WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.300
Hi, my name is Riva and I'm a linguist who uses R.

00:00:10.300 --> 00:00:14.160
Seven years ago I tried to learn R and I failed.

00:00:14.160 --> 00:00:18.559
I wasn't sure where to start my R journey, so as someone with a background in humanities

00:00:18.559 --> 00:00:21.760
I thought the best option was reading a book.

00:00:21.760 --> 00:00:26.299
I wanted to make one of those cool plots with a great background I've seen around to communicate

00:00:26.299 --> 00:00:27.660
some results.

00:00:27.660 --> 00:00:31.280
So I picked a book that promised me that I will learn the most important elements of

00:00:31.280 --> 00:00:32.660
R.

00:00:32.660 --> 00:00:37.820
On page 99 I was still reading about defining class and methods, trying to understand what

00:00:37.820 --> 00:00:43.660
an array was and how to multiply its elements, but hadn't done anything with real data yet.

00:00:43.660 --> 00:00:46.660
The problem, I think, were my expectations.

00:00:46.660 --> 00:00:51.419
I was expecting learning resources that helped me say things with data, but all I found were

00:00:51.419 --> 00:00:56.119
description of rules that didn't make much sense to me as a beginner.

00:00:56.119 --> 00:01:01.080
It was very difficult for me to see how I can use these rules with the data I had, and

00:01:01.080 --> 00:01:06.879
how I will jump from these abstract descriptions to, for example, making a plot.

00:01:06.879 --> 00:01:10.959
It felt like trying to learn a second language only by reading a grammar book and not by

00:01:10.959 --> 00:01:14.639
interacting with actual human beings.

00:01:14.639 --> 00:01:18.959
The thing is that learning a programming language has many similarities with learning a second

00:01:18.959 --> 00:01:20.639
language.

00:01:20.639 --> 00:01:21.959
But what does this mean?

00:01:21.959 --> 00:01:25.720
How can this idea be applied to the design of learning resources?

00:01:25.720 --> 00:01:28.400
Or when choosing them to guide your learning path?

00:01:28.400 --> 00:01:33.160
And how can you take this into account when developing a package, for example?

00:01:33.160 --> 00:01:37.199
First, let's talk about learning.

00:01:37.199 --> 00:01:40.839
Not everyone learns a second language with the same purposes.

00:01:40.839 --> 00:01:43.279
The same happened with programming languages.

00:01:43.279 --> 00:01:47.480
I failed learning R the first time because I wasn't the expected audience for the book

00:01:47.480 --> 00:01:48.480
I chose.

00:01:48.480 --> 00:01:53.220
At the moment, I just wanted to be an R user, not a programmer.

00:01:53.220 --> 00:01:57.339
Not everyone is learning R to be a linguist or a grammarian of the language.

00:01:57.339 --> 00:02:01.500
There are surely people that want a deep understanding of how the language works.

00:02:01.500 --> 00:02:05.019
And those are the people who are contributing to its development.

00:02:05.019 --> 00:02:10.380
But there are tons of people that just want to use R to do things, like making a plot,

00:02:10.380 --> 00:02:13.619
or running a statistical model, or creating reports.

00:02:13.619 --> 00:02:17.619
I failed the first time I tried to learn R because the book I chose for learning was

00:02:17.619 --> 00:02:22.639
the equivalent of a grammar book of R. Descriptions of how the language works and the names and

00:02:22.639 --> 00:02:25.440
purposes of all its different parts.

00:02:25.440 --> 00:02:29.000
And as a beginner, or as someone who just wants to learn the language to communicate

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:32.679
your data to others, that is not what is more useful.

00:02:32.679 --> 00:02:36.759
What you need is something that works more like a textbook.

00:02:36.759 --> 00:02:40.199
Textbooks for learning a second language always start the same.

00:02:40.199 --> 00:02:44.679
You learn how to say hello, how to introduce yourself, and some simple sentences to communicate

00:02:44.679 --> 00:02:46.639
meaning to others.

00:02:46.639 --> 00:02:49.960
Even books for learning dead languages have this approach.

00:02:49.960 --> 00:02:53.080
I had to learn a little bit of Latin as an undergrad.

00:02:53.080 --> 00:02:58.199
And the first thing we learned was how to ask someone who they are and how to respond

00:02:58.199 --> 00:02:59.880
to that question.

00:02:59.880 --> 00:03:06.199
I even learned how to insult someone in Latin, a language in which the last native speaker

00:03:06.199 --> 00:03:09.240
died centuries ago.

00:03:09.240 --> 00:03:13.320
Textbooks start this way because they are built around people's needs and knowledge,

00:03:13.320 --> 00:03:15.279
not around language rules.

00:03:15.279 --> 00:03:21.880
In textbooks, you learn first what you can do with a language, not how the language works.

00:03:21.880 --> 00:03:27.240
In language teaching, this is called a communicative approach, and is based on the idea that learning

00:03:27.240 --> 00:03:32.759
a language successfully comes from having to communicate real meaning to real people.

00:03:32.759 --> 00:03:37.520
Throughout the different lessons in a textbook, you learn new words and structures, and new

00:03:37.520 --> 00:03:41.119
contexts where to use those words and structures.

00:03:41.119 --> 00:03:45.520
The grammar rules behind those real-life examples are only explained after you learn

00:03:45.520 --> 00:03:51.679
how to use them, and if an old if is really necessary for you to know them.

00:03:51.679 --> 00:03:55.119
In textbooks, scaffolding works as a spiral.

00:03:55.119 --> 00:04:00.119
You learn something in one lesson, and then come back to that content in the next lesson,

00:04:00.119 --> 00:04:05.279
but now showing more ways to use what you learn, how to adapt it to different situations,

00:04:05.279 --> 00:04:11.080
and how to combine the words and structures you know in new ways.

00:04:11.080 --> 00:04:14.320
It's like copy and pasting, and then adapting.

00:04:14.320 --> 00:04:19.959
You learn how to use a new language structure, like how to ask a question, and then you learn

00:04:19.959 --> 00:04:25.839
how to adapt it to your own needs, to solve the problems you are interested in.

00:04:25.839 --> 00:04:32.239
It's this ability to adapt language structures to new situations what makes us flexible users,

00:04:32.239 --> 00:04:35.760
in both natural languages and programming ones.

00:04:35.760 --> 00:04:41.559
For example, we first learn how to create one type of plot using all the default settings,

00:04:41.559 --> 00:04:46.200
and then we come back to that content to add more complexity to the visualization, like

00:04:46.200 --> 00:04:51.239
mapping more variables, using different geoms, or making annotations.

00:04:51.239 --> 00:04:55.279
And we build those new skills over the ones we learned previously.

00:04:55.279 --> 00:05:00.160
This copy, pasting, and adapting is also the strategy we use with examples we find in Stack

00:05:00.160 --> 00:05:03.519
Overflow or our studio community.

00:05:03.519 --> 00:05:07.600
We bring to our script something that worked in another context, and then try to figure

00:05:07.600 --> 00:05:11.200
out how to adapt it to our own needs.

00:05:11.200 --> 00:05:15.839
Sometimes we are not even sure why it worked, but after doing it a couple of times, we start

00:05:15.839 --> 00:05:19.600
inferring what is going on behind the scenes.

00:05:19.600 --> 00:05:24.440
You don't need to know all the grammar rules to be understood in a language, and you don't

00:05:24.440 --> 00:05:29.279
need to know the name of all its structures to be a competent user.

00:05:29.279 --> 00:05:32.920
Even native speakers don't know the name of all the parts.

00:05:32.920 --> 00:05:38.559
You probably don't know what a paratactic or a hypotactic clause complex is, but you

00:05:38.559 --> 00:05:41.220
definitely know how to use one.

00:05:41.220 --> 00:05:45.559
If you are a native English speaker, you know how to correctly pronounce every case of two

00:05:45.559 --> 00:05:51.760
O's together in words like moon, book, floor, flood, something very, very difficult for

00:05:51.760 --> 00:05:54.000
us not-native speakers.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:57.959
But you probably don't know why they are pronounced differently.

00:05:57.959 --> 00:06:01.600
The adults who raise you didn't write you a grammar book for you to acquire your native

00:06:01.600 --> 00:06:02.600
language.

00:06:02.600 --> 00:06:06.279
They didn't teach you the grammar rules.

00:06:06.279 --> 00:06:08.760
They talked to you and let you talk.

00:06:08.760 --> 00:06:10.720
They probably read you books.

00:06:10.720 --> 00:06:12.899
You sang or sang together.

00:06:12.899 --> 00:06:16.679
You did things with words progressively more complex.

00:06:16.679 --> 00:06:20.320
In the same way, you don't need to know all the rules of a programming language to be

00:06:20.320 --> 00:06:23.239
able to do things with it.

00:06:23.239 --> 00:06:24.880
What rules do you need?

00:06:24.880 --> 00:06:28.799
The ones that can help you achieve the purposes you're seeking.

00:06:28.799 --> 00:06:32.859
If you need to customize a plot in a very precise way because the default options are

00:06:32.859 --> 00:06:39.359
not what you need, then learning how a theme works in ggplot is relevant, not before.

00:06:39.359 --> 00:06:44.000
If you need to work with arrays, then learning what they are and what kind of things you

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:48.140
can do with them is relevant, not before.

00:06:48.140 --> 00:06:49.640
One more thing about textbooks.

00:06:49.640 --> 00:06:52.779
They usually have learner personas.

00:06:52.779 --> 00:06:56.940
If you're learning a language because you want to travel, the first chapters will probably

00:06:56.940 --> 00:07:02.220
show you how to get along in the airport and ask for directions in a city.

00:07:02.220 --> 00:07:06.619
If you're learning the language because you're going to study abroad, the first chapters

00:07:06.619 --> 00:07:10.959
will probably be about students trying to find something in the campus or dealing with

00:07:10.959 --> 00:07:13.140
university bureaucracy.

00:07:13.140 --> 00:07:16.660
The same happens with programming learning resources.

00:07:16.660 --> 00:07:20.799
Fortunately, in the past couple of years, a lot of online resources have appeared to

00:07:20.799 --> 00:07:25.000
learn R and other programming languages, and many of them are focused on the needs

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:26.559
of specific users.

00:07:26.559 --> 00:07:32.200
So all the data and examples are connected with what those specific users need and know.

00:07:32.200 --> 00:07:37.279
So taking into account the community approach when teaching programming language involves

00:07:37.279 --> 00:07:44.079
doing real things from day or page one, building complexity as a spiral, revealing rules after

00:07:44.079 --> 00:07:48.839
you know how and when to use them, and only the ones that can help you achieve what you're

00:07:48.839 --> 00:07:50.820
looking for.

00:07:50.820 --> 00:07:55.200
And taking into account who your learner personas are.

00:07:55.200 --> 00:07:59.640
In the last couple of years, a lot of R resources have been created taking into account these

00:07:59.640 --> 00:08:01.559
principles.

00:08:01.559 --> 00:08:06.519
Learning resources that let you experiment first and then build explanations.

00:08:06.519 --> 00:08:12.839
Books that show you the whole game first and then explain the details behind every step.

00:08:12.839 --> 00:08:17.040
Publications that had in mind different learner personas with different backgrounds that show

00:08:17.040 --> 00:08:22.559
you how to do relevant things with relevant data for your field.

00:08:22.559 --> 00:08:24.260
But hey, what about the other books?

00:08:24.260 --> 00:08:26.160
The ones that explain how R works?

00:08:26.160 --> 00:08:29.079
Well, those actually are very cool books.

00:08:29.079 --> 00:08:32.320
I'm a linguist myself, so I really love grammar books.

00:08:32.320 --> 00:08:36.559
But for both natural and programming languages, they're not the first step to approach a language

00:08:36.559 --> 00:08:42.359
when what you want is to learn how to use it and how to communicate with other people.

00:08:42.359 --> 00:08:47.520
What is this communicative approach only relevant for people teaching or learning R?

00:08:47.520 --> 00:08:49.099
What about programmers?

00:08:49.099 --> 00:08:51.359
What about people developing packages?

00:08:51.359 --> 00:08:55.679
Well, thinking package development from a communicative point of view can also help

00:08:55.679 --> 00:09:00.640
us in issues like developing more useful error messages and documentation.

00:09:00.640 --> 00:09:03.559
Let's take a look at error messages first.

00:09:03.559 --> 00:09:08.440
Whatever you're learning, having feedback is the kind of thing that can help you improve.

00:09:08.479 --> 00:09:15.000
This applies to any human activity, from sports to cooking, from knitting to language learning.

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:20.799
Having this in mind, let's take a look at two error messages addressing the same problem.

00:09:20.799 --> 00:09:26.280
We all have been here, putting one instead of two equal signs to filter a column.

00:09:26.280 --> 00:09:29.039
This is the error message you get in base R.

00:09:29.039 --> 00:09:35.679
It says error unexpected equal sign in, and then the part of the code where the unexpected

00:09:35.679 --> 00:09:38.000
equal sign is.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:42.719
Our message here is pointing you where your mistake is, but there is no clue on how to

00:09:42.719 --> 00:09:43.719
solve it.

00:09:43.719 --> 00:09:46.679
Why is the equal sign unexpected?

00:09:46.679 --> 00:09:48.880
Should I put something else?

00:09:48.880 --> 00:09:53.679
And if you're not an English speaker, there is even more enigmatic.

00:09:53.679 --> 00:09:57.039
Pointing errors is not the same as giving feedback.

00:09:57.039 --> 00:10:01.859
To learn from your mistakes, you not only need to know where the error is, but you need

00:10:01.859 --> 00:10:06.880
some clues on how to solve it, so next time you know what to do.

00:10:06.880 --> 00:10:10.599
Let's take a look at the message for the same error, but using the filter function

00:10:10.599 --> 00:10:12.799
from Dplyr.

00:10:12.799 --> 00:10:17.400
Your message says, error, problem with filter, input one.

00:10:17.400 --> 00:10:19.200
Input one is name.

00:10:19.200 --> 00:10:23.239
This usually means that you have used one equal sign instead of two.

00:10:23.239 --> 00:10:26.679
Did you mean country two equal signs Chile?

00:10:26.679 --> 00:10:30.479
Run rlang last error to see where the error occurred.

00:10:30.479 --> 00:10:36.679
This message let us know what the problem is, its probable origin, a suggestion how

00:10:36.679 --> 00:10:41.840
it can be solved, and if and only if you want to know where your code failed, how to

00:10:41.840 --> 00:10:44.799
take a detailed look.

00:10:44.799 --> 00:10:47.200
What we have here is feedback.

00:10:47.200 --> 00:10:52.239
We not only learn the origin of the problem and how to solve it, but also how we can take

00:10:52.239 --> 00:10:56.200
a deeper look at the code to see where the error occurred.

00:10:56.200 --> 00:10:59.640
And if you're not an English speaker, you can put this on Google Translate and we'll

00:10:59.640 --> 00:11:02.200
get something useful.

00:11:02.200 --> 00:11:07.679
These couple of extra lines in your function code can make a lot of people, can make the

00:11:07.679 --> 00:11:13.039
life of many people easier and help them fail in a way they can learn.

00:11:13.039 --> 00:11:18.200
Giving useful feedback is the best way to learn how to overcome difficulties.

00:11:18.200 --> 00:11:22.719
And this is something we do all the time when someone is learning our native language.

00:11:22.719 --> 00:11:27.080
If you don't understand what they are trying to communicate to you, you usually say things

00:11:27.119 --> 00:11:32.039
like, sorry, did you mean... and try to rephrase what they said to check if you understand

00:11:32.039 --> 00:11:34.000
correctly their intention.

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:40.320
We don't go around saying people lack of subject matter agreement or misplaced modifiers.

00:11:40.320 --> 00:11:44.559
We don't do that because it is not really helpful for learners.

00:11:44.559 --> 00:11:50.039
It's more effective to give cues on how to fix the problem and show how a correct version

00:11:50.039 --> 00:11:51.880
might look like.

00:11:51.880 --> 00:11:56.200
So if you're a package developer and want people to be happy users with your package,

00:11:56.200 --> 00:12:00.559
you can think about how your error messages can give guidance.

00:12:00.559 --> 00:12:06.280
But error messages are not the only part of a package that can adopt a communicative approach.

00:12:06.280 --> 00:12:09.359
Let's take a look at documentation.

00:12:09.359 --> 00:12:11.479
Function documentation is great.

00:12:11.479 --> 00:12:15.239
Sometimes you forget the name of an argument and taking the help page can allow you to

00:12:15.239 --> 00:12:17.619
solve this kind of issue.

00:12:17.619 --> 00:12:21.640
But to use it, you need to know the actual name of the function you're after.

00:12:21.640 --> 00:12:24.359
Otherwise it's kind of useless.

00:12:24.359 --> 00:12:28.919
What if you know the problem you want to solve, but not the name of the function that can

00:12:28.919 --> 00:12:31.479
help you solve it?

00:12:31.479 --> 00:12:34.520
Function documentation are like dictionaries.

00:12:34.520 --> 00:12:38.760
They have the definition of the words you can use in a programming language.

00:12:38.760 --> 00:12:42.880
But we don't learn a language by memorizing words from the dictionary.

00:12:42.880 --> 00:12:47.039
We need to learn how to use the words, in what context they are useful, what kind of

00:12:47.039 --> 00:12:50.840
meaning can we construct with them?

00:12:50.840 --> 00:12:53.919
What if you don't know the name of the function you need?

00:12:53.919 --> 00:12:58.679
What if you know what you want to achieve, but not what functions can be useful for that?

00:12:58.679 --> 00:13:01.760
Well, here comes vignettes.

00:13:01.760 --> 00:13:05.880
Vignettes are an awesome resource to describe the problem that your package is designed

00:13:05.880 --> 00:13:09.280
to solve and to show people how to solve it.

00:13:09.280 --> 00:13:15.359
They are a great resource to show how to do things with your package with real example.

00:13:15.359 --> 00:13:17.799
And they are easy to find using a search engine.

00:13:17.799 --> 00:13:21.520
So they are also a great way to promote your package.

00:13:21.520 --> 00:13:25.880
In a vignette, you can explain with details the different categories your functions are

00:13:25.880 --> 00:13:32.760
divided, how you can coordinate multiple functions to solve problems, and show extended examples

00:13:32.760 --> 00:13:37.039
that people can copy, paste, and adapt to meet their own needs.

00:13:37.039 --> 00:13:42.119
The best part is that vignettes are easy to create using the uses package.

00:13:42.119 --> 00:13:46.159
With uses-use-vignettes, you can create one.

00:13:46.159 --> 00:13:51.080
So thinking of error messages as a way to give feedback to the users of your package

00:13:51.080 --> 00:13:55.799
and writing vignettes that explain how to do things with the functions you create are

00:13:55.799 --> 00:14:01.359
great ways to think about package development from a communicative approach.

00:14:01.359 --> 00:14:02.359
Two closing remarks.

00:14:02.359 --> 00:14:07.000
Is RubyR the best programming language to learn?

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:08.000
Isn't Python better?

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:10.260
Or what about Julia?

00:14:10.260 --> 00:14:14.599
With programming languages, it happens the same as with natural languages.

00:14:14.599 --> 00:14:17.960
There is no one intrinsically better than the other.

00:14:17.960 --> 00:14:21.679
The best programming language is the one that can help you solve more effectively the

00:14:21.679 --> 00:14:25.919
problem you are trying to solve in the context you currently are.

00:14:25.919 --> 00:14:31.280
Sometimes, things like processing time or number of lines of code are important to take

00:14:31.280 --> 00:14:32.679
into account.

00:14:32.679 --> 00:14:34.880
But sometimes they are not.

00:14:34.880 --> 00:14:39.919
And only what is easier or faster for you to write, not the computer to process, is

00:14:39.919 --> 00:14:41.840
more important.

00:14:41.840 --> 00:14:46.799
And sometimes it's more relevant what programming language your audience can understand.

00:14:46.799 --> 00:14:49.760
The same happens with natural languages.

00:14:49.760 --> 00:14:55.119
Right now, I would really prefer to be speaking in Spanish, but it's definitely more effective

00:14:55.119 --> 00:14:56.760
if I speak in English.

00:14:56.760 --> 00:14:57.760
Why?

00:14:57.760 --> 00:15:01.239
Not because of any characteristic of English language itself.

00:15:01.239 --> 00:15:06.479
Actually, for this subject in particular, Spanish is way more precise, because we have

00:15:06.479 --> 00:15:08.760
more words to speak about language.

00:15:08.760 --> 00:15:14.400
We make distinctions like lengua, lenguaje, idioma, all of which have different and precise

00:15:14.400 --> 00:15:15.400
meanings.

00:15:15.400 --> 00:15:19.200
So I need to use more words in English to explain those concepts.

00:15:19.200 --> 00:15:24.320
But right now, being able to convey my message to a broader audience is more important than

00:15:24.320 --> 00:15:28.799
the lexical variety or precision that Spanish offers to this subject.

00:15:28.799 --> 00:15:31.239
So which programming language to learn?

00:15:31.239 --> 00:15:35.880
The one that can help you best solve the problems you are interested in, and that allows you

00:15:35.880 --> 00:15:40.960
to speak with the people you are interested in communicating with at that moment.

00:15:41.599 --> 00:15:47.760
And with natural language, knowing, the same way as with natural languages, knowing more

00:15:47.760 --> 00:15:52.840
than one allows you to communicate with more people and do more things with words.

00:15:52.840 --> 00:15:57.679
And this leads us to the second closing remark.

00:15:57.679 --> 00:16:01.599
Communication and community has the same etymology.

00:16:01.599 --> 00:16:06.119
A communicative approach in programming languages is important because it can help us build

00:16:06.239 --> 00:16:11.200
stronger communities where everyone can be part of the conversation.

00:16:11.200 --> 00:16:15.479
New people learning the language can offer new and diverse perspectives, and we should

00:16:15.479 --> 00:16:17.280
cherish that.

00:16:17.280 --> 00:16:22.760
There is no one correct way to learn a programming language, but there are many things that can

00:16:22.760 --> 00:16:27.440
be done to make it more effective and enjoyable.

00:16:27.440 --> 00:16:32.280
Failing to offer people opportunities to learn in an easier way, or thinking that the only

00:16:32.280 --> 00:16:37.320
way to learn a programming language is the hard way, is not only kind of a gatekeeping

00:16:37.320 --> 00:16:40.000
issue, but it's also dangerous.

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:43.760
Because the most dangerous thing that can happen to a natural or a programming language

00:16:43.760 --> 00:16:47.400
is not having a vibrant community of users to keep it alive and evolving.

